metadata.name: <iframes> #384
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: VOYAGERS #141
metadata.description:
Generative animated painting made from looping gestures in a virtual void.

Voyagers is an exploration of automated gestures and screenspace layering effects. Each brush stroke sweeps through the canvas leaving a trail of color that either disappears or mixes with adjacent colors. The image slowly builds up to achieve an equilibrium between the rhythm of the gestures and the interaction of color values. These colors are quantized and dithered to produce chunky, textured, blocks of light that reify the materiality of the screen and the pixel. Two aspect ratios are possible, each with its own material relationship to screen-based work, 1:1 and 4:3 (vertical).

Press 's' to save looping animated GIF (live mode only).
Press 'p' to pause the animation.
Press 'c' to capture a single frame.
Made with P5.js and GLSL. By @galoandstuff.

metadata.name: AUTOJOURNEYPAINT #23
metadata.description:
An automatic painting journey

AUTOJOURNEYPAINT  uses a series of custom built walkers to make plots with a great variety of properties, including packing gaps, directions and propensity for turning. These plots are then drawn over with varying, incremented pixel brushes.

AUTOJOURNEYPAINT chooses color for itself from a broad list of more than 100 colors. It selects a palette of 8 but might not use all of them.

The background consists of a single color at the back and then one channel (either r, g, b) of the same color iterating from 0 to 255 while also iterating over a number of pixels within a border, all fixed to a pixel grid of variable size. The iteration over pixel numbers means the background produces very different patterns at different screen sizes

If you want to know more about the variables used they are output in the console log

Responsive to screen size. Larger resolutions will implement more brush strokes.

Some renders may be slower due to more complex collision detection in some brush settings.

Press “s” to save the image as a png.

metadata.name: AMazingArt(YouAreAMazing2.1) #115
metadata.description:
A collection of playable, colorful, and often *very challenging* generative-art mazes.

V2.1 is a hybrid analog-vs-digital generative-art collection, re-released with a fully populated features-list for collectors, and *improved in-game physics* for gamers!

One of 2 distinct color-aware maze-generator algorithms build your unique and fully-playable mazes, choosing their path by sampling pixels from the background-image chosen from a portfolio of 35 original works of art, created by PureMattness between 2019 and 2022. Each maze's solution and color-palette are unuique; Both are created on-the-fly by the generator.


** There are billions of possible mazes to be generated! **


Mazes also have distinct physics in gameplay mode.

... oh yeah, did I mention that these mazes are PLAYABLE??

After the genesis animation completes, on PC, press 'g' to play, or 'h' to reveal the solution.
On mobile, touch below or left of the maze to play, above or right for the solution.

In game mode:
On PC, use [W,A,S,D] to move. To return to the maze overview, hold 'q' for 3 seconds.
On mobile, touch the maze to move. Remain still for 30 seconds to quit.


Because these mazes are sometimes difficult to solve, each one is equipped with visual "hints"
to help you along your way. Some maze's hints are easy to see and pop up frequently,
others are difficult to see and rarely appear.
Keep an eye out for them!


----------

Features:

4 levels of grid 'tidiness' (clean, lived-in, untidy, squiggly)
5 maze sizes (small, medium large, macro, full)
5 levels of roominess (Claustrophobic, Tight, Small, Roomy, Spacious)

2 generator algorithms:
- Growing Tree 
- Blobby Recursive Likeness-following Subdivider

5 Color-sample radii (used to colorize grid-vertices)
5 color-affinities (oblivious, indifferent, observant, interested, obsessed)

35 base images (listed below)
136 position/size/rotation combinations are possible for each image.


Game-mode Features:

1800+ combinations of hint-types (7 styles, 6 rates, 3 durations, 3 envelopes, 5 likelihoods)
3 levels of player traction
4 player acceleration-rates

----------

metadata.name: Swimmer #29
metadata.description:
I am interested in the eye getting caught in an ambiguous shape that can remind you a fish or a jellyfish, a buffalo or a crazy hairy dog, a mollusk or a protozoan, a dragon or an entity from another dimension.
I am interested in your eyes going through the figure, riding with it, and having fun in the reverie of possibilities that travels to nowhere.

The code, made in P5js, has random factors that define the texture of the background, the vertical amplitude of the movement, the length of the hair or the colors, that can be on black and white, pastel range, variable colors or variable colors with stripes.

By Diego de los Campos 2022
NFT License 2.0

metadata.name: SoulFish #62
metadata.description:
Named after the artist Wu Che-Yu, the soul fish was born in the void and crystallized from human emotions.

Fluttering silently and slowly, their bodies almost disappeared in the light of the deep sea.
The fish swims freely, and this is the happiness of the fish.
If we are not a fish, how do we know the joy of a fish?
How do we know that we do not know the joy of fish?
We will only learn about it when we come to the riverside.

Inspired by Zhuāngzǐ: "The Debate on the Joy of Fish" c. 3rd century BC

Interactivities:
> Key S: Save
> Holding mouse in different directions: Swim 
> Click and let the fish touch the Bubbles
> Key B: Toggle border
> Key P: Pause

metadata.name: SC.002 : Studies Series #95
metadata.description:
This hybrid project combines elements of 2 previous drops: Glomularus + Inertial Packing. The project is intended as a giveaway to show appreciation to the community of collectors who previously have minted my work.

SC.002 includes multiple constraint systems, based on Verlet and Euler Integration approaches, with attached geometric primitives and softbody Prototubes. Numerous user controls are included:

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
-, +: reduce | increase Node Count
{, }: reduce | increase Packing Dimension
c, v: reduce | increase Node Adhesion
h, j: reduce | increase Node Jitter
b, n: disable| enable Node-Node Collision
z, x: reduce | increase Stick Constraint
a, s: hide | show Nodes
q, w: hide | show Wireframe
d, f: reduce | increase Prototube Thickness
p: screen capture

Tip:
1. There are 8 unique geometries, should you be inclined to collect a full set.
2. Bringing values outside of "rational" range is encouraged.

Note:
Please post your favorite SC.002 screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node
